Tungsten? Sounds expensive. The old "beehive" rounds in 105mm just had steel darts in them. They were basically finishing nails with the heads mashed into a set of little fins to make them fly straight. The shell had eight thousand flechettes in it and an electronic timer with a blackpowder bursting charge to split it open when it got to the desired distance. They actually worked pretty well, unlike the 90mm time fuzed explosive rounds they used in Vietnam... those had mechanical timers and the engineers hadn't considered that getting boosted up from a standing start to almost a mile a second in twenty feet of gun barrel would mash all the little gears and springs flat and destroy the timer every time.
